         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translation</head>
            <p> Octavia the sister of Caesar Augustus (set up by) the Cyrenaeans
</p>
            <p/></div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p><!-- PIR -->This is the full sister of Augustus, mother of Marcellus who was his natural heir in the twenties B.C., sometime wife of M. Antonius.
               She was highly honoured in Rome (cf Dio Cassius XLIX.38.1) but comparatively few memorials to her have come to light in the provinces,
               although the mention of her at Mytilene (IG XII.2.58.b, line 25, available at <bibl><title>PHI</title> <citedRange n="PH74715">74715</citedRange></bibl>) suggests that she would figure in any representation of the imperial family.
               </p>
     <p>This monument cannot be earlier than 27 B.C. when the title of Augustus was conferred
        and perhaps not later than 4 B.C. when she died (although that is an insecure proposal).
        There is no obvious clue to the reason for it and no certain evidence for other imperial monuments in this sanctuary
        unless <ref type="inscription">C94100</ref> (for Livia in or after C.E. 14) belongs there, which is not certain.
     </p>
            <p>The spelling of Octavia’s nomen in Greek at Cyrene is variable.</p>
         </div>
         
